transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Thank you for calling customer service, I can help you.

Speaker 2: Oh, is this Score Blue?

Speaker 1: Yes, sir.

Speaker 2: Hi, I received a message saying the clinician needs more information from me.

Speaker 1: However, I got a message, a chat from her last night saying that they have everything they need.

Speaker 2: Okay, let me pull you up.

Speaker 1: What's your name and birthday?

Speaker 2: My name is Larry Sharfstein, S-C-H-A-R-F-S-T-E-I-N, 12-20-1954.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: So what happened was you were asking when will my prescription be mailed to me and those kinds of questions the doctor can answer.

Speaker 1: So the message you were sent, it was just basically saying to call us to ask any of those questions.

Speaker 2: But the way that it pops up to you is that the doctor has more information because it's coming from, like, the doctor's office.

Speaker 1: But that's not the actual message.

Speaker 2: And then the assistant of the doctor said, like, we have everything, we don't need anything.

Speaker 1: So you're good to go.

Speaker 2: Okay, so I just sit back and wait for them to show up.

Speaker 1: Whenever there's something in the chat, you're going to receive that message about the doctor has more information.

Speaker 2: Even when the doctor writes the prescription, that will pop up.

Speaker 1: Okay, so I'm all good, right?

Speaker 2: Nothing I need to do but wait.

Speaker 1: No, sir.

Speaker 2: Okay, and how long does it usually take?

Speaker 1: Three, four business days per day?

Speaker 2: So today is Monday.

Speaker 1: Your doctor is going to write the prescription today.

Speaker 2: And then it will be three, four business days.

Speaker 1: So it will be, like, Friday.

Speaker 2: All right, sounds good.

Speaker 1: Thank you very much.

Speaker 2: You're welcome.

Speaker 1: Have a wonderful day.

Speaker 2: Bye-bye.

Speaker 1: Bye.
